Re “Any time you try to access an indeterminate value, you invoke undefined behavior”: This is not correct. By itself, reading an indeterminate value merely gives you some value. There are situations in which reading an uninitialized object has undefined behavior, but they have further criteria. Also note: The C standard uses “access” to mean reading or writing, so accessing an object with indeterminate value is of course not a problem when you are writing it.

These pixel class values are then converted to a one-hot encoded vector for each pixel to produce the truth (`y_true`). The network predicts a one-hot encoded value for each pixel (final `softmax` activation) ie `y_pred`.
